properties.abstract: Parisian flair in Thurgau. Tracing the Napoleonic family's footsteps, you discover picturesque gardens and magnificent castles. The route leads through a mosaic of fields and orchards with spectacular views over the Untersee. Enjoy the panoramic views of the Alps, Vorarlberg and the Allgäu from the Napoleon Tower.
properties.description:
The route begins in Mannenbach-Salenstein and leads up to Arenenberg Castle, one of the most scenic vantage points in the Lake Constance region. The castle sits in a park and garden with an over 600-year-old tradition. In Medieval times, Thurgau and Constance patricians created a pleasure garden here. In the 19th century, the site was converted into a large landscape park under Queen Hortense, the mother of Louis Napoleon.

The imperial family settled in Arenenberg Castle after Emperor Napoleon I was deposed and exiled. Louis Napoleon, later Napoleon III and the last Emperor of France, lived here as a youth and young adult. The family brought Parisian flair to Thurgau, and in the Arenenberg Napoleon Museum, visitors stroll through the magnificent salons and original rooms. 

From the museum, the path continues to Salenstein Castle. It belonged to Charles Parquin, who at the time took on the construction of the Napoleon Tower along with Louis Napoleon.

The route leads along forest paths to Helsighausen and then mainly flat to the Napoleon Tower Hohenrain near Wäldi. The viewing platform offers breathtaking panoramic views. To the east, the view stretches to Vorarlberg and the Allgäu, while the stunning Swiss alpine panorama beckons to the south. Below you, a colourful patchwork of forests, fields and orchards extends. By the way, anyone who wanted to visit the lookout tower as a private person at the time had to pay the sum of six kreuzers, equivalent to about CHF 100 in today's purchasing power. 

Following the route eastward, you cross the Nüwil forest and reach the Bommer Weiher shortly afterwards. The protected area is an important habitat for water birds and amphibians. From here, the hike's destination Siegershausen is only a stone's throw away.
